text=!Machine learning, creation, discovery... intelligence?%0a!!!Carlo A. Trugenberger, 31.3.2023%0aArtificial intelligence, after its heyday in the 80s of last century, has been a%0arenewed hot topic for experts since the deep learning revolution of the early%0a10s of the present one. After the disruption of generative chatbots late last year,%0ait is on the lips of everyone.%0a%0aSince the word intelligence is a subject of heated debate though, let us focus%0afirst on the less controversial concept of machine learning. Machine learning%0atechniques are broadly divided into two categories, supervised and%0aunsupervised. The aim of supervised algorithms is to learn a function that maps%0ainputs to outputs based on available labelled examples of this function. This can%0abe done with discriminative or generative techniques but, in all cases, there is%0aa human teacher who knows the function, at least on the training set. The%0atrained software is thus nothing more than a supporting tool to overcome the%0aproblem of applications to large data sets.%0a%0aUnsupervised learning is essentially pattern recognition. These algorithms try%0ato identify by themselves relevant patterns within huge sets of unlabeled and%0aunclassified data, with no human guidance. The task itself is not simple at all.%0aOn top of this, two questions immediately arise, which further complicate the%0aissue:%0a%0a* What should be done with the identified patterns?%0a* Are all patterns admissible?%0a%0aThese questions are not independent, of course, the answer to the second%0aquestion largely depends on the answer to the first. And forgetting to properly%0aaddress the second question is what often causes many problems, like the%0afailures experienced by the present generation of generative chatbots.%0aLet us consider music-generating algorithms as a first example. In this case, the%0atask is to produce new music pieces that closely resemble one, or a set of,%0apatterns previously identified in the listening phase. There are not many%0arestrictions on the admissible patterns in this case, music (and art in general)%0ais quite subjective, and one can easily find an enthusiast for works that others%0amay find less appealing.%0a%0aThe same procedure is blindly applied to language in chatbots, unfortunately.%0aThese are trained to recognize patterns in huge quantities of text and are then%0aasked to answer with similar patterns to new questions. This of course leads to%0adisasters, like in this answer,%0aQuestion: what happens if I hold a piece of paper horizontally with two hands%0aand I let go of one hand?%0a%0aChatGPT answer: if you were holding a piece of paper horizontally with two%0ahands and let go of one hand, the paper would likely tilt or rotate in thedirection of the hand you let go of. This is because the paper is no longer being%0aheld evenly on both sides, and the weight distribution is now uneven. If the%0apaper is a light weight, it will drift to the side where you let go of and fall to the%0aground. If the paper has a little more weight or if you have a strong grip, it will%0astay in the air for a moment before falling down.%0a%0aThis failure could have been anticipated. The point is that language, contrary to%0amusic, is subject to a huge number of constraints: those of meaning, or in%0asimpler words, making sense. Most identified patterns, like most possible%0asentences, must be rejected, simply because they lack any sense. What is%0amissing in present generative chatbot are the constraints imposed by%0asemantics.%0a%0aThere are two ways to satisfy constraints on the admissible patterns. Either the%0asystem must learn them by brute force in a large number of interactions with%0aseveral instances of itself, with a positive reward (essentially life vs. death) for%0aremaining within the permitted bounds, or they must be hard-wired by humans.%0aThe first way is evolution, the second is a pragmatic shortcut.%0a%0aThe evolutionary path is what has been followed by the creators of AlphaGo%0aZero, the algorithm that beat the best human Go player in 2016. The program%0ainitially knew only the rules; it then played against itself for many days using%0areinforcement learning to hone its skills until it became the worlds best player.%0aWhat is most interesting is that, in its learning process, AlphaGo Zero developed%0anew, very effective strategies that were unknown and surprising to the best%0ahuman players. This is undeniably the process of discovery and,%0acorrespondingly, it may be argued that the program is indeed intelligent,%0aalbeit on a specific and limited domain. Personally, I fully agree with this point.%0a%0aWhile the Go game is extremely complex in its strategic development, the basic%0arules are quite simple. This cannot be said about language, unfortunately. The%0acomplexity of semantics, the set of rules governing meaning in human%0acommunications is humungous. This is already true of lexical semantics,%0agoverning the meanings of words and their relations. But things get really out%0aof control with logical semantics, concerned with concepts such as reference,%0apresupposition and implication. It could be even surmised that an algorithm%0awhich learns semantics from scratch in interactions with instances of itself%0aretraces human evolution and acquires general intelligence, i.e., consciousness.%0a%0aUnfortunately, I believe this is still far over the horizon. A more pragmatic,%0aalbeit less elegant, approach is to hard-wire the rules of lexical semantics in an%0aalgorithm that combines a linguistic approach with pattern recognition%0amachine learning methods. This is what has been done by InfoCodex Semantic%0aTechnologies. Since this software is enabled for actual content recognition, it is%0acapable of discovery, which it has proved by finding new biomarkers for%0adiabetes only on the basis of text mining a large quantity of biomedical research.%0aMoreover, it can summarize large documents on any subject without specific%0atraining, a task which is outside the scope of chatbots based exclusively on%0aprobabilistic language models.%0a%0aAnother difficult question is, if a machine learning algorithm can acquire the%0acapabilities for independent scientific discovery. Here too, there are two levels.%0aIn mathematics, a system of axioms is a circumscribed set of rules which is%0asomewhat similar in its nature to the rules of a game like Go. And indeed, once%0athese rules are programed, automated reasoning and deduction algorithms can%0aprove new theorems, exactly like AlphaGo Zero can find new strategies.%0a%0aHowever, suppose that an algorithm is shown a huge quantity of data on the%0adistribution of galaxies in the universe and asked to detect patterns in this data.%0aCan it then infer from these patterns a new law for galaxy formation? Of%0acourse not! This is as impossible as for chatbots to discover new knowledge from%0atext patterns. In this case, what is missed is the entire status quo of scientific%0aknowledge accumulated in the history of humanity. This is infinitely more%0acomplex than the simple rules of an axiomatic system, a complexity%0acomparable, if not superior to the logical semantics of human communication.%0aCan an algorithm learn this knowledge by accelerated interactions with%0ainstances of itself coupled with some form of rewards? In this case too, I fear%0athis is not yet on the horizon. And unfortunately, in this case the shortcut of%0ahard-wiring at least a subset of the needed concepts is also not feasible;%0ascientific discoveries stem often from unsuspected correlations and similarities%0abetween very distant fields.%0a%0aThe debate about the possible intelligence of machines can be sometimes%0avirulent. It looks to me, however, that both sides just focus on unproductive%0adogmatic positions. Programs like AlphaGo Zero undeniably show some form of%0aintelligence, although it is evidently not complete human intelligence, and one%0ashould not read too much into it. The ideology that machines cannot acquire%0ahuman-like intelligence in principle is also just an antiquated anthropocentric%0adogma. After all we acquired our own intelligence in evolution and there is%0anothing stopping in principle algorithms to go through an immensely%0aaccelerated evolution in interactions with themselves. In the meantime, the%0ashortcut of hard-wiring some semantics and combine it with machine learning%0acan lead to a pragmatic way to simulate some intelligence and make some%0adiscoveries.
